00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:11.360
your version of "One
Thousand and One Nights"?

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:12.660
&gt;&gt; Salman Rushdie:
Well, the "One Thousand

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:15.120
and One Nights" was just a
way of thinking about it.

00:04:15.120 --> 00:04:19.430
So, it doesn't really have any
narrative connection with the

00:04:19.430 --> 00:04:20.730
"One Thousand and One Nights".

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:22.320
It's just that kind of story.

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:26.190
I mean one of the things
I thought about all these

00:04:26.190 --> 00:04:29.980
so called Wonder Tales in the East,

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:31.750
which is not just the
"Arabian Nights".

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:34.760
In India there're so
many other collections.

00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:39.830
There's wonderful collection of
animal fables, the "Panchatantra".

00:04:39.830 --> 00:04:44.200
And actually from Kashmir which is
where my family is originally from,

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:48.690
there's a very large story
compendium originally

00:04:48.690 --> 00:04:54.310
in Sanskrit written by Somadeva
called the "Ocean of the Streams

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:57.870
of Story", Kathasaritsagara,
which is actually longer

00:04:57.870 --> 00:04:59.390
than the "Arabian Nights".

00:04:59.390 --> 00:05:04.880
So, there are many of these things
around and they were, in many ways,

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:08.380
some of the first stories I
heard and the first things I--

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:12.430
first literature that I fell in
love with and originally heard them

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:14.750
as children's bedtime stories.

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:18.200
And when I grew up to
read the actual books,

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:21.080
it immediately struck me that these
books are not written for children,

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:25.760
you know, that the language in
them is very complex and the ideas

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:29.360
in them are very complex and
they're clearly adult fiction.

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:32.070
And that interested
me in a different way.

00:05:32.070 --> 00:05:34.500
And so, after finishing the memoir,

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:38.400
I thought in a way I found
myself circling back to that kind

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:43.710 position:56%
of origin point of the place where
my interest in literature had began.

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:45.010
And I thought what can I do?

00:05:45.010 --> 00:05:50.440
Is there some way that I can
use that kind of storytelling

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:54.340
but to tell a contemporary story,
you know, not to do something set

00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:57.040
in the Baghdad, the Harun
al-Rashid or something,

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:01.230
but something set in
New York City now.

00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:02.610
And I also wanted to
do another thing,

00:06:02.610 --> 00:06:04.870
which is that I'm also
very interested in the kind

00:06:04.870 --> 00:06:08.040
of Western surrealist tradition.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:10.070
You know, and there
are so many writers

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:12.950
and so many different
languages who have all written

00:06:12.950 --> 00:06:15.560
in a kind of non-naturalistic way.

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:20.240 position:56%
I mean, you know, you could say that
Kafka is a magic realist, you know?

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:22.710
And in Russia, Gogol and
Bulgakov and then, of course,

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:24.750 position:56%
there's French surrealist and so on.

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:27.180
And I've always been
very interested in that.

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:32.250
So I thought what would happen
if I allow this Eastern tradition

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:37.980
of the fantastic to collide with a
Western tradition of the fantastic?

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:39.930
And, you know, what
would that look like?

00:06:39.930 --> 00:06:42.050 position:56%
And I guess the answer is this book.

00:06:42.050 --> 00:06:44.940
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: And the results
