00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:40.760
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: Right.

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:42.060
&gt;&gt; Salman Rushdie: The end.

00:08:42.060 --> 00:08:43.360
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: The genie is.

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:44.660
[ Laughter ]

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:45.960
.

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:47.260
&gt;&gt; Salman Rushdie: Yeah.

00:08:47.260 --> 00:08:48.560
And now, that's what you call a
big narrative engine, you know?

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:49.860
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: Yeah.

00:08:49.860 --> 00:08:51.160
&gt;&gt; Salman Rushdie:
And yet, you know,

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:54.340
his way of telling the story is
so extraordinary that it becomes,

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:57.290
you know, one of the
greatest novels I've written.

00:08:57.290 --> 00:09:01.170
But I've always thought my
way of thinking about it is

00:09:01.170 --> 00:09:03.480
that if you're going
to build a big car,

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:06.150
you should put a big
engine in it, you know?

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:08.570
And story is the engine.

00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:11.750
And I've always thought that
there are a lot of books

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:16.470
which are underpowered because they
don't have that narrative drive.

00:09:16.470 --> 00:09:19.480
But in the-- You know, in the
18th century, the 19th century,

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:23.160 position:56%
in those great moments of the novel,
the great writers never forgot

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:24.930
to tell stories, you know?

00:09:24.930 --> 00:09:28.680
I mean, Dickens is crowded with
stories and so as Thackeray.

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:30.570
So, you know, all of those writers.

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:35.150
So, I'm very interested in--

00:09:35.150 --> 00:09:38.140
I see there's no reason
at all why storytelling

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:41.940
and literature should be separated
from each other, and I think one

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:46.390
of the things I've tried to do is
to, you know, is to use stories

00:09:46.390 --> 00:09:49.550
