00:23:48.110 --> 00:23:49.410
So--

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:50.710
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: OK.

00:23:50.710 --> 00:23:52.010
&gt;&gt; Salman Rushdie: --
you might have to--

00:23:52.010 --> 00:23:53.310
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: OK.

00:23:53.310 --> 00:23:54.610
&gt;&gt; Salman Rushdie: We might have
to come back in a couple of years.

00:23:54.610 --> 00:23:55.960
But I do think that-- you know,
I'll just say one thing about it,

00:23:55.960 --> 00:24:03.060
which is that it seems to
me that the thrust of a lot

00:24:03.060 --> 00:24:08.710
of contemporary identity politics
is to ask us to define ourselves

00:24:08.710 --> 00:24:12.450
in increasingly narrow ways.

00:24:12.450 --> 00:24:18.200
We have to be very
specific things, you know?

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:21.090
That's true in politics, politics.

00:24:21.090 --> 00:24:22.560
It's true in gender politics.

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:23.950
It's true in race politics.

00:24:23.950 --> 00:24:25.250
It's true everywhere.

00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:27.950
We are being asked to define
ourselves more narrowly.

00:24:27.950 --> 00:24:31.570
And the trouble with that is

00:24:31.570 --> 00:24:35.120
that the more narrowly we define
ourselves, the easier it is

00:24:35.120 --> 00:24:38.580
to find ourselves at odds
with other people, you know,

00:24:38.580 --> 00:24:43.330
whereas one of the things that the
novel as a form has always known is

00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:46.780
that human beings are
very, very plural people.

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:49.320
We are not singular, we are plural.

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:52.240
And we are contradictory, you know?

00:24:52.240 --> 00:24:54.830
I mean, that's what's
been famously said,

00:24:54.830 --> 00:24:56.320
you know, do I contradict myself?

00:24:56.320 --> 00:24:58.510
Very well, I contradict myself.

00:24:58.510 --> 00:24:59.810
And that's what the novel is like.

00:24:59.810 --> 00:25:03.360
It shows that a human
character is not homogenous,

00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:05.160
it's heterogeneous
and contradictory.

00:25:05.160 --> 00:25:09.300
So, you know, anybody in this
room could probably make a couple

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:13.300
of dozen statements
that would be all

00:25:13.300 --> 00:25:16.570
of them would be equally
a definition of identity.

00:25:16.570 --> 00:25:23.250
They could define themselves as,
for example, tall or supporters

00:25:23.250 --> 00:25:29.360
of a certain baseball team or
as the parents of their children

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:32.970
or as people who do a certain
kind of job or in terms

00:25:32.970 --> 00:25:35.970
of whatever their religious
orientation or lack of it might be.

00:25:35.970 --> 00:25:39.080
I mean there's a whole range of
things you can say about yourself.

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:41.120
And all of them are true.

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:45.470 position:56%
And if you accept that you are all
those things, then it becomes easier

00:25:45.470 --> 00:25:47.480
to find points of overlap
with other people.

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:51.420
You can have strong political
disagreements with somebody

00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:53.870
but support the same football team.

00:25:53.870 --> 00:25:56.300
You know, you could--
it's just much easier.

00:25:56.300 --> 00:26:00.720
When you see human character as
plural, it becomes much easier

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:03.490
to see points of contact
with other people.

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:09.020
And the more you have to say, you
know, I am Western, I am Muslim,

00:26:09.020 --> 00:26:11.840
et cetera, that's hard to
create conflict, you know?

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:14.850
And I think that's the
problem with a lot of--

00:26:14.850 --> 00:26:17.060
And it's not even in
the West versus Islam.

00:26:17.060 --> 00:26:22.950 position:56%
I mean in India right now, you know,
the desire to push people into kind

00:26:22.950 --> 00:26:29.750 position:56%
of narrow community definitions, you
know, Hindu, Muslim, Sikh, whatever,

00:26:29.750 --> 00:26:32.740
is also creating conflict there.

00:26:32.740 --> 00:26:36.800 position:56%
So, I worry about this whole area of
identity politics because it seems

00:26:36.800 --> 00:26:41.180 position:56%
to me, to not understand something
very profound about human nature was

00:26:41.180 --> 00:26:44.840
that all identities are not
singular, they are plural.

00:26:44.840 --> 00:26:47.760 position:56%
And the novel has always known this.

00:26:47.760 --> 00:26:50.440
And it's one of the reasons I
think why people should read novels

00:26:50.440 --> 00:26:54.720
because it tells them something
that they're not hearing enough.

00:26:54.720 --> 00:26:57.760
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: And you've
said it's the age of frontiers

00:26:57.760 --> 00:27:00.590
that we live in that it's the
time to-- that the people--

00:27:00.590 --> 00:27:04.070
you know, one of the sort of goals
of your creative project has been

00:27:04.070 --> 00:27:06.700
to explore the idea of
those who step across lines,

00:27:06.700 --> 00:27:08.200
those who don't see frontiers.

00:27:08.200 --> 00:27:09.500
&gt;&gt; Salman Rushdie: Yeah.

00:27:09.500 --> 00:27:14.710
And I'm the kind of opposite
