00:30:17.310 --> 00:30:21.400
there is Jhumpa Lahiri from South
Asia, there's Yiyun Li from China,

00:30:21.400 --> 00:30:23.570
there's Nam Le from
Vietnam, there's, you know,

00:30:23.570 --> 00:30:27.330
any number of people coming
from all over the world

00:30:27.330 --> 00:30:29.700
that they have their families
coming from all over the world

00:30:29.700 --> 00:30:33.490
with different stories in
their luggage, you know?

00:30:33.490 --> 00:30:37.600
And unpacking that luggage and
allowing those stories to escape

00:30:37.600 --> 00:30:39.420
into American literature, you know,

00:30:39.420 --> 00:30:41.490
and become a part of
American literature.

00:30:41.490 --> 00:30:46.620
And I think it has been incredibly
enriching of this generation

00:30:46.620 --> 00:30:48.840
of American writers have.

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:52.380
And I-- in a way, I was--
this book is in part inspired

00:30:52.380 --> 00:30:57.250
by those young writers because I
thought I can do that, you know?

00:30:57.250 --> 00:31:00.730
I thought I've got stuff
