00:33:09.120 --> 00:33:11.530
to become the adult in order to--

00:33:11.530 --> 00:33:13.500
because of the incompetence
of adults.

00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:16.830
So, the fact that my father lost
my story about "The Wizard of Oz",

00:33:16.830 --> 00:33:22.650
it's completely appropriate to
the theme of "The Wizard of Oz".

00:33:22.650 --> 00:33:29.200
But no, I mean, I think I was
very lucky that when I was young--

00:33:29.200 --> 00:33:31.290
when I was like in the
years I was in college,

00:33:31.290 --> 00:33:35.010
I was in Cambridge from--
in the mid '60s, '65 to '68.

00:33:35.010 --> 00:33:40.540
I mean, there's a period from
roughly speaking, the late 1950s

00:33:40.540 --> 00:33:44.940
to the early 1970s, which we
now think of as the golden age

00:33:44.940 --> 00:33:46.570
of the sound cinema, you know?

00:33:46.570 --> 00:33:50.000
And it's very difficult to
explain to people what it felt

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:53.850
like when what we now
think of as masterpieces

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:56.550
with that week's new
movie, you know?

00:33:56.550 --> 00:34:02.120
So, one week, it would be,
you know, "La Dolce Vita",

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:05.430
and the next week it
would be a new Godard film

00:34:05.430 --> 00:34:10.480
and then a new Truffaut film
and then a new Pasolini film

00:34:10.480 --> 00:34:14.870
and then a new Ingmar Bergman film
and then a new Satyajit Ray film

00:34:14.870 --> 00:34:17.130
and then a new Luis Bunuel film.

00:34:17.130 --> 00:34:19.850
And week after week
after week, this--

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:23.400
I mean, it was dazzling
to go to the cinema.

00:34:23.400 --> 00:34:27.640
And I think I learnt
at least as much

00:34:27.640 --> 00:34:30.430
in the movie theaters
