00:52:24.730 --> 00:52:30.500
I just think it's a way
of training the mind.

00:52:30.500 --> 00:52:36.740
First of all, it allows you
to understand beauty in a way

00:52:36.740 --> 00:52:38.680
that you don't understand
unless you have it

00:52:38.680 --> 00:52:40.060
at your fingertips, you know?

00:52:40.060 --> 00:52:45.530
If you have a poem there in your
head for you to think about,

00:52:45.530 --> 00:52:48.470
you can appreciate it in a way
that you don't on the page.

00:52:48.470 --> 00:52:52.220
When the page becomes irrelevant
because it's inside you,

00:52:52.220 --> 00:52:53.980
that's a different
sort of experience.

00:52:53.980 --> 00:52:57.850
And I just think it's
an enriching experience,

00:52:57.850 --> 00:53:00.400
although I admit annoying.

00:53:00.400 --> 00:53:05.390 position:56%
And children, young people very
often complain about being asked to,

00:53:05.390 --> 00:53:07.010
you know, rote learning
is something.

00:53:07.010 --> 00:53:13.720
And it's also unfashionable, which
is its second great advantage.

00:53:13.720 --> 00:53:17.440
So, yeah, I mean, I
think it's a good thing.

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:22.940 position:56%
And, I mean, I know everyone I know
who spent their childhood being made

00:53:22.940 --> 00:53:26.500
to learn things speaks
well of the experience,

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:29.990
says that they are glad they
did and that they feel happy

00:53:29.990 --> 00:53:31.380
to have those things in their head.

00:53:31.380 --> 00:53:34.440 position:56%
And not everything stays in your
head but, you know, some stuff does.

00:53:34.440 --> 00:53:37.230
And it's worth it, it's
worth it, you know?

00:53:37.230 --> 00:53:41.510
It gives you a frame of
reference which is broader

00:53:41.510 --> 00:53:42.960
than you would otherwise have.

00:53:42.960 --> 00:53:45.590
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: Thank you.

00:53:45.590 --> 00:53:48.080
